commentBody:
@Thad 

I would have been scratching my head over that one.  The only meaning of "full of beans" is a bowdlerization when you can't say what you think a person is really full of.

The meaning of being lively is something I learned today years ago.  I don't believe I've ever heard or seen it used that way.

@Steve L 

Note:  I left out two words:  The only meaning of "full of beans" I KNEW...

If it's in the dictionary, I'm not disputing that it exists.

@Steve L 

I'm just now getting to the book review that @Andrzej shared a few days ago, and it addresses this in the third paragraph:

<a href="https://theguardian.com/books/2025/jan/02/gobsmacked-by-ben-yagoda-review-the-british-invasion-of-american-english" target="_blank">https://theguardian.com/books/2025/jan/02/gobsmacked-by-ben-yagoda-review-the-british-invasion-of-american-english</a>

@Steve L 

The only person I remember using "full of beans" to mean lively was my grandmother.

She was born in 1898.

@Rick Y.

For your interest:

<a href="https://merriam-webster.com/grammar/is-that-lie-bald-faced-or-bold-faced-or-barefaced" target="_blank">https://merriam-webster.com/grammar/is-that-lie-bald-faced-or-bold-faced-or-barefaced</a>

@B I thought it was bold for this reason which you somehow skipped from the same article: 

"bold in manner or conduct," or "impudent"

I don't see how that's LESS clever.

@Sean  

You may not be able to see it on the device you're using, but in the clue "It's hard to 
believe," the "lie" in the middle of believe is in BOLD face type.

@Sean Surprised me, too, but only because I sadly missed the formatting hints entirely when solving... haha 

As @dutchiris points out, in the clue 'hard to believe', [lie] is in bold. Likewise, [ism] is capitalised in 'dismantle' of 17a, [ion] is subscript in 'conditioned' of 27a etc. 

As a writer I don't love it, but for a themed puzzle, it's fun, and creative at that. :)

@B 
Granted, before I twigged to this puzzle’s gimmick, I had BaLDFACED— but only BOLDFACED fits with the theme! Of course it was intentional! 

Language evolves, as indicated in the Merriam- Webster article cited in the column… but that article certainly doesn’t say “bold-faced” is a “mistake”. Did you read it carelessly? I’d hate to think you are feeding us a….

@Sean 
Lots of back-and-forth on this so far. 
Just want to put my vote in for bare-faced, which is the phrase I grew up hearing (if you get my drift).

@Heidi and especially @B

And BOLD-FACED in that expression has the lucky coincidence of also meaning "more obvious than normal" because of its association with typefaces.  I think it's quite appropriate, and that's the association people have with it:  typefaces, not people's faces.

In other words, it's the lie that's in bold face.

@Scott 
I've been a font addict since 1984 Mac and its many fonts. Papyrus has its place.  But Albertus is my first love. Helvetica & Times are so boring. 
Is it wrong to have over 250 fonts on my Mac?

@Scott 
Have you found Village?  
The font from the TV show, derived from Albertus.

@Sam Lyons I hope none of the crossword setters use ChatGPT for "research," given that it's not a search engine and doesn't even claim to give accurate answers, which is good, since it very rarely does.

Which "Irena" did it suggest for Turgenev?

Happy Tuesday to you too, but please reconsider using ChatGPT as a research tool.

@Graham Hackett 

People don't usually prominently place a phrase that no one would recognize in the chorus and the title of a song.  The fact that this happened means that the phrase, in its contracted form, was known and in use at least as early as 1959 (and probably considerably earlier), when the song was released.

That was 65 years ago.

@Andrzej 
And, of course, the correct term is actually bare-faced. 
But language will evolve!

@Sam Lyons 
I can confirm Comic Sans is easier to read for a dyslexic. Both my sons and husband struggle with the usual Romans or Helvetica (definitely a genetic link) so I got used to typing in CS; proof reading/correcting for DH work, ditto homework plus messaging for the boys as they grew. My daughter and I don’t suffer from Dyslexia and can read anything, though I dislike the more flowery scripts on an aesthetic basis.
I came a cropper once though. I did my BA Lit while my kids were young and used to unthinkingly submit essays in CS, which were accepted ok until my third year and a very snotty professor of Children’s Literature (the irony) got quite exercised about it. I explained the history behind my choice, but was v firmly told to submit in Romans henceforth. Nice woman.

