@Vaer , thanks.

Didn't know that was the name of the Patti LaBelle song. Rang no bells for me.

So, it seems that the theme was rather free-wheeling. Ladies of all types, not just drag queens or movies.

@John Carson 
Like I said, I was very surprised to see Lady B.  She and her annual  festival, Wigstock, were widely covered by NYC media in the 80s and 90s, but I wouldn't have thought they were well-known by the general population. 
Then again, I've never watched Ru Paul's Drag Race and it's possible she has some kind of role there that these days that people might know her from.

@Sam 
The only puzzles that have titles are Sunday puzzles, and if you are on the phone app, you can find it on the page that opens when you press the i icon.
If you're talking about the title of the Wordplay column, that is the work of the columnist and/or the editorial team, and may reference the puzzle or one its clues or fill.

@Sam 

Ah yes, there are themes in early-week puzzles, but not titles. Sundays get both themes and titles for them! 

Occasionally, theme clues are clearly labeled, such as with an asterisk. Sometimes their answers have visibly different squares in the grid. Today's had neither... So a trip to the columb may be in order -- as it was for me today!

@CCNY came here specifically to point out that "BOLDfaced"  is simply not correct -- an
 minor illiteracy, if there is such a thing.

I liked the puzzle otherwise.

@Lewis 
Delight for you, but not for me. While I finished the puzzle without having to look up anything, I didn't appreciate having to work so hard on a Tuesday puzzle. 

I wonder, with all due respect, if you ever met a puzzle you didn't like.

@redweather 

When the puzzle has features that the print version you use can't support, you can only get the newspaper version.

Perhaps there's something wrong with your settings...

@Times Rita 
I Saved as a PDF, then printed with Fit to Page, and everything showed up, including the clue #s.
I learned that from someone here a while back...!

@Dan 
Aren't "champing" and "chomping' the same thing, though? They're both onomatopoeia for biting down on something.

In fact, when I look up the definition of "champ," the definition given is "chomp."

@Sue Stolbach:
Oh, boy, can I relate to that! I broke a 1200+ streak a while back when I forgot to go back and fix a typo on a Monday. I tried to take the advice of others to let the streaks go…but within a month I was back to counting days. And now, after puzzling through two major surgeries and a trip to Paris, I’m within twenty days of breaking my old record. Wish me luck!
The “Monday” part of it was the worst, wasn’t it?

