It's 9 degrees here, but my radiators are dialed up to 11 and I cannot control them. I've been wearing tank tops and shorts inside, but when I go out I have to put on long undies. It is confusing.

@Linda Jo 
OMG

NO!  I just came back from checking my print-out, and there is no slash.  So I'm not nuts..

@Grant 

In Italian, just as in Polish, both are valid answers to "Thank you".

In most everyday situations, especially among people who know each other well, it is more common to answer "Dziękuję" (Thank you) with "Nie ma za co" (It was nothing) than with "Proszę" (You're welcome, pretty much, effectively).

@Grant 

If someone thanks you in Italian ("Grazie!"), you can answer either "Prego" (in this context, "You're welcome!") or "Di niente!"
"Bitte" in German works much the same way as "Prego" in Italian.

@Peas Corps 

At one point I was working for a BMW dealer in Atlanta. They have a web site for parts; the staff for that consisted of my boss, an additional person to help him with contacting customers, and me, in the warehouse, packing and shipping everything. We shipped out everything from tiny seals to shipments containing every part needed to repair the entire smashed front end of a car, and we shipped all over the world, to Australia, to Hong Kong, even (weirdly) to Germany.

At the time, the weight limit for UPS packages was, I think, 70 or 80 pounds (up to 150 now). You just don't crate up stuff like that. If I had something that got shipped strapped to a pallet or crated up or was heavy enough to require a forklift, it always went via a carrier like DHL.

@pat in oregon 
I stopped listening to NPR in 2020 when I realized that it was putting me in a state of permanent anxiety. I still contribute, but I seldom listen anymore. I scan the NYT, but that's about it. I vote for progressives and liberals and I don't immerse myself in stuff I can do nothing about.

I recently made myself turn on NPR; they (no kidding) were doing a story about the decrease in the number of people following the news because of stress.

@Man and 2 dogs

As a new crossword solver at my current skill level I am pretty much only at a Monday/Tuesday level solve.

So when puzzles like this come around where it is obviously a more difficult solve (I couldn’t even get anywhere close on this particular one) it’s just so inaccessible to new puzzle solvers, to where my two puzzles a week turns into one puzzle a week.

@sonnel 100%!

This tripped me up when I was solving the puzzle, and I begrudgingly inputted the “O” only when the cross made it clear that this was the only option…but looking back at the clue, the bolded “lie” makes it absolutely clear what the author was going for.

All the dictionary-consulting debate about bold vs. bald is completely besides the point, IMO.

@Wark welcome and you are so right. That being said, I’m sure the constructors understand what people are like and don’t take it too personally. Over time, I’ve actually started to come here just to see what people are complaining about each day. 

For example, I was expecting all kinds of complaints about whether this was an appropriate Tuesday puzzle, but the constructor and the column saw that coming and already addressed it at length. 

For the constructor: great job. Loved the puzzle and thought many of the clues were unique and clever. I love to see some new slang like “yeets.”

